animal.description:
Baby is now our longest canine resident. We would love to find her the perfect home for the holidays!
At this point we think she would be best as an only pet, all though she has done well her with some submissive type male dogs, in the long run it might cause issues down the road as she can be territorial. 

Baby was an owner surrender. She takes a little while to warm up to strangers and is leash shy if roaming free. Once she gets comfortable with you she's very much glued to your hip. She knows how to sit and lay down but won't do it unless she's super comfortable with you. She was housed with another dog and did fine until a recent move which is why she ended up here. She doesn't seem bothered by any of the dogs here and has been non reactive through the fence. She will need someone with patience and a quiet home to regain confidence in herself. She is 2 years old and 52#.

Breed Guess: Pit mix

Gender: Spayed Female
Children: Unknown at this time
Cats: Did okay in our cat room
Dogs: Meet and Greet required 
Housebroken: Unknown
Adoption fee: $300.00

Stormy came to us with a badly injured paw. She is still in the cone of shame as the paw is slowly healing. She is very good about getting her bandages changed, and she'll need continued care for this wound to heal properly. She is super sweet and cuddly. If Stormy could be for you, please fill out an application today. 

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs are also microchipped.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description: Hi there! I am very excited to meet you! I am a friendly dog that likes to be touched, I like it so much I will even roll over onto my back for you. I do, however, need some training; I do not know my basic commands and I need to learn how to walk on a leash. I am also a very good bouncer so my future home must be fully enclosed with a fence tall enough to keep me in. I love my toys! I will definitely be needing lots of those in my new home. I like to play fetch and the best part of it is that I bring the toys back and drop them. Unfortunately, I am not perfect. Despite taking treats gently from your hand, I do get possessive over my raw hide and do not appreciate it being taken away from me. Also, please leave my food bowl alone. Now when it comes to dogs I just get so excited seeing one!! I will pull and jump on two feet towards one in an attempt to meet! I am a bit rude meeting other dogs because I don't respect boundaries I suppose. :( So I do believe I need further socialization when it comes to meeting new dogs. Overall, I think I would do great in an adult only, experienced household. If I fit your lifestyle, I hope to meet you soon!

animal.description:
Meet Fred! Fred is the Love Buggiest Fred you'll ever meet. He burps. He sighs and snores like a bulldozer. He sometimes smells. But beneath all that, he is the ultimate lap dog. He wants nothing more than sit in your lap, gaze into your eyes, and give you the sloppiest kiss you've ever received. He gives love eyes. He purrs. He will cuddle with his head on your shoulder. He LOVES food. Like seriously. He. Loves. Food.

Fred has a number of health issues that we are treating. He is significantly malnourished and positive for Lyme. Fred’s health is improving every day, and his goofy personality is really starting to shine through.

During time in his foster home, Fred has gotten along with two other large dogs after a slow introduction. He has not been around cats or children so we are unsure about his behavior around them. Fred is still working on potty training, especially since he needs to go potty often on his current (and temporary) medications.

Fred loves bed time. He hops into his crate, gets a treat, and within 10 minutes he is sawing logs. Fred’s new family will have the opportunity to teach him commands like sit and stay since he hasn’t quite picked them up yet.

If you want to fully experience the Fred, help Fred with his long recovery, and give him a lifetime home, please submit an adoption application and we can schedule a socially-distanced meet and greet with Fred in his foster's backyard.

Fred is getting up-to-date on his vaccinations and is estimated to be between 1-2 years old. He has been neutered and microchipped. Fred is good with other dogs his size after a slow introduction. Unsure of how he would respond to small dogs or cats. Fred has spent time with children as young as three and behaved really well.

animal.description: FOSTER PLACEMENT PARAMETERS: Personality: Shy at first. Take some time to let him warm up and he becomes a sweet boy! Dogs: Suitable in a home with other dogs. Prefers females and socially appropriate dogs. Cats/Small Animals: Same as above. If you have small dogs you should expect to come meet him with your dogs first before being sent home with him. Children: Suitable in a home with children. Energy Level: Moderate. Likes to play tug and fetch. Food/Object Possession: Shows competitiveness with food and food toys. Please take that into consideration especially if you have other animals in the home. Separation Anxiety: Unsure. Potty Trained: Does not seem to be potty trained. Can be managed though. ***Behavior may change once in a stable home environment. This is a summary of behaviors noticed and tested for during the animals stay at the shelter.*** Chili has been in foster care, this is what his foster dad had to share about him... Sweet boy that just wants snuggles and play. Potty training is in the works but constant attention is needed so he does not go inside the house. He does great in cars, walks and on bike rides. Lots of love to give. He gets a little mouthy while petting but can be easily distracted by toys and things to chew on. He gets very excited around other people and dogs but is very gentle and kind. Separation anxiety is a potential concern hopefully crate training will help.

animal.description: Jessie unfortunately had to be surrendered to the shelter because his owners because they thought he needed more space than they could provide him with. Their notes on him say that he was great around their 13 year old son, but he was starting to have some problems getting along with their other, smaller dog. Jessie, like most animals surrendered by their owners, is finding the shelter to be very scary and stressful. That fear sometimes causes him to act out. He is very protective of his kennel, and he makes people earn his trust. He really only feels comfortable around the people he sees on a regular basis. Once he trusts you, he's as sweet as can be and he'll happily let you leash him up and take him out for a walk as well as pet himit just takes him awhile to build up to that point with new people. He loves treats, especially beef or bacon favored treats - that's one way to help build trust with him!

animal.description:
MEET LUNA!  Luna is a sweet and playful Chihuahua mix.  She's in need of a special foster or forever home that can focus on her as the only pet in the house.  She has some anxiety-driven behavior that she needs help with.  This includes running after her tail, and biting her tail.  This may sound like playful behavior, but for Luna it's actually a way of dispelling her anxiety.  Luna needs to be gently redirected when she displays this behavior, and encouraged to calm down in other ways.  She's looking for a patient and kind person with a calm and quiet house to make her foster home, or even her forever home!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.KodaBear is a very handsome young Pyr who will be arriving at Old Farm Kennels in Florence, MT on January 30th. This young guy can be the most loving boy ever - but he has a couple of issues that need to be worked on before he can be adopted out. First thing is the boy is going to be neutered on February 5.... but even before that is done he will be worked with about giving up things that he isn't supposed to have.... which is why he is available in the first place.

KodaBear's owner loves him deeply and is very sad to have given him up, but he did bite her when she found him on a countertop with a skillet that she had used to fry hamburger. He does NOT like to give up things that he wants, and when she reached for the skillet he reached for her hand... not good.

Once that issue is under control this young man will make someone a wonderful buddy. He loves being outdoors and maybe he could learn to provide protection to a hobby farm of some sort. Lots to figure out before this boy will be sent to a new home.

Feel free to stop by Old Farm Kennel and meet KodaBear and the other dogs we have boarded there. Best visiting times are from 10a.m. to 4p.m.

animal.description:
Meet Charlie!

Looking for a small, 23 pound, 9 year old walking buddy? Need a friend to take a road trip with? Want someone who will sleep in his OWN bed? If you answered yes, I might be your guy. I need a safe place to “hang up my leash,” if you get my drift. 

I just LOVE to go on walks, every day if possible! I would love a quiet home with maybe one other small dog (or I can be your one & only). Bigger dogs stress me out. I don’t need to be cuddled, but I do like to be petted and loved on my terms. I’m sensitive at times, so be careful touching my face, ears, or feet. I need a person who will listen to me when I let them know I don't want to be touched, so kids are a no go for me.

Let’s talk about my favorite subject...food! I absolutely LOVE food; dog food and human food. I’m getting better about this, but I may whine, bark, or beg for your food. Sorry, it’s a bad habit I developed many years ago. Here’s a positive-I love carrots and cucumbers for a snack! Mmmm. 

I’ve got some anxiety and have started taking a special medicine, which seems to be helping me relax and enjoy life a bit more. I also take joint supplements, which help me stay active. 

If you think I’m your next buddy, please apply so you can meet me. The name is Charlie!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs are also microchipped.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description:
Why Choose Me?

*Sugar has $200 in sponsorship for rescue!*

Update 12/31: Sugar has been treated for heartworms (received her Diroban shots). She will need to be on crate rest for the next month while the worms die off, but she’s on her way to being healthy! Please wish this sweet girl well while she recovers.

Update 12/4: Look at Sugar! She’s come so far, and it’s because she’s been in a home with an amazing foster mom. When Sugar first came to the pound, she hid in the back of her kennel shaking. She didn’t know anything about walking on a leash and had to be carried. Today, she walked easily on a leash and would come to me for pets and treats. Instead of hiding beneath the table, she hopped on it to sit with me. Sugar is still shy, but that’s okay. She’s super sweet and doing well. Her life is so much better. Since she has heartworms, Sugar is only available to rescues or a foster-to-adopt. Hopefully, one day she’ll have her forever home. Being in a foster home has given her that chance.

Update 10/16: Sugar is making progress in being more comfortable with people. Unfortunately, she has tested positive for heartworms. While Athenspets & ACCAS will help with the cost of treatment, a rescue should be prepared for some added expense and the exercise restrictions of treatment. To learn more about preventing and treating heartworms, please go to the American Heartworm Society’s website: https://www.heartwormsociety.org/pet-owner-resources

Sugar could use some sweet kindness in her life. She’s always lived outside, and when her owners moved, they just left her behind. She had been on her own for so long that it took time to catch her and bring her to the shelter. Sugar is frightened, and when I first met her, she was visibly shaking and her tail was tucked tight. I sat on the bench and waited as she checked out her surroundings. Eventually, she didn’t run when I approached and let me scratch her back and behind her ears. Even though she was uncertain, she never snapped at me. 

When she finally took treats from me, I felt like she was a little more comfortable though I know it will take time for her to feel safe and at ease. Until that happens, Sugar is only available to rescues. How wonderful it would be for her to be rescued and finally know what it’s like to be cared for and loved.

If you are interested in rescuing Sugar, call 706-613-3540 to discuss options with staff.

You can read more about this dog and check out additional photos here: https://athenspets.net/Adoptables/54142-sugar/ OR check out our urgent dogs (http://tinyurl.com/Athenspets-FB-URGENT-Dogs) on Facebook!

This dog is currently at Athens-Clarke County Animal Control, located at 125 Buddy Christian Way, Athens, GA. For the most timely information on hours, location, availability and how to adopt, call the shelter any day from 10am-4pm at 706-613-3540 or go to https://www.athensclarkecounty.com/133/Animal-Control.

Dogs: Meet and Greet required

Adoption fee: $325.00

Trooper is a sweet guy. He is a little shy at first as all Dalmatians are. Once he warms up, he loves to give hugs and kisses! He is a fence climber so he will have to have supervised yard time at all times! If this handsome guy could be for you, please fill out an application today!

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs are also microchipped.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

Meet Butch - 3½- 4 yr old, Boxer/ Great Dane Mix.  Butch has now been available for adoption for 2 years!!  He is available with the Friends of Glocester Animal Shelter in Rhode Island! 

He was adopted for 3 weeks,  but absolutely refused to get along with the cat in the house.  Butch needs a special home,  and we will be extremely picky about where he goes - he can easily be set up for failure,  and we won't allow that.  Butch is an energetic,  protective,  attention craving,  job seeking, loving boy.  He needs a firm,  but patient person.  He will walk all over you (sometimes literally) if allowed,  but he's very eager to please, and highly trainable. He has learned everything he knows with positive reinforcement and the use of a "mom voice".  

**He needs a home with no children,  and no cats but probably best in a home all of his own. His new person/people need to understand that he will never be a super social dog. He's a ladies man,  but will attach to a male in the house over time. 

If you think this big lug sounds like he could fit into your life,  please call and make an appointment to come visit and discuss your plans for his forever home. (401)568-3885.
Email: Aco@glocesterri.org

animal.description: Hello. My name is Gatsby. My adoption fee is $350 in Houston, TX and $550 in Bellevue, WA (includes health cert and travel fee). I am up to date on all my vaccinations, neuter, and microchip. I also tested Heartworm Negative. Gatsby is such a sweetheart. He doesn't have a mean bone in his body. He is a lover. He wants to be with his person all the time. He is a lapdog and does not wait for an invitation to jump up in your lap. He gets along fine with other dogs and loves a good game of zooming around the backyard with them. He is starting to eat all of his food now but does need encouragement as he is easily distracted. He loves treats too. He is working on potty training but does mark at times. He understands what no means and will stop any bad behavior when told the "no" word. I'm sure he would be fine around older, considerate kids. He has seen my cat from another room and joins in with the others at barking at her. He doesn't like the crate and will voice his complaints. He will jump up on the bed, the couch and unfortunately even the table. He needs training. If he could be with a family where there is someone at home with him during the day, that would be ideal. He also likes to sleep in bed with his person but will accept sleeping on the couch if that is an option.

animal.description: Hi there. My name is Hudson, but my foster mom calls me Huddy or Weirdo, and Im a Powderpuff Chinese Crested. Im not naked because Im sick..Im naked because thats what my breed is likewere all mostly hairless! Youd think that would be a problem up here in the Great White North, but Ive got lots of jackets and pajamas to keep me warmplus, I love, love, love to cuddle under a blanket with my people! Speaking of people.I love them. I love kids. I love ladies. I love men. If youre a two-legger, we can be bestiesbut Im a little bit particular about my dog friends. Im sort of selfish with my toys and chewies, and will growl at any other dog that looks at them, so Id do best either as an only dog, or with a dog that doesnt really mind sharing. If there arent toys or chewies around, I like to play with other dogs. In my current house, I love to chase and bark at the other dogsuntil they turn around, then I realize how big they are and I run away, but I like it when they chase me. I would also do best in a home where I can be left to roam when my humans arent home because I really, really, really dont like kennels. I will scratch myself raw trying to get out. Im really good loose in the house.although, sometimes I do use the bathroom in thereespecially if Im not let out right away in the morning. Im not a fan of going outside in the snow, but my foster mom just puts booties and a jacket on me, and then Ill run through the snow with the big dogs to do my business, no problem. The last thing is that I am an allergy dog. I have indoor and outdoor allergies, but I am currently on a 10 month course of allergy shots that help keep them in check. My foster mom gives me a shot once every couple days, and Im really good about getting them. I dont mind at all. My foster mom keeps my nails cut short so that I cant damage my skin when its itchy, and Im really good about getting them cut too.I just lay on my back and she snip-snip-snips them short. Easy peasy. My foster mom says to tell you that shell miss me a lot, and that whoever gets me has to promise to only use her for dog sitting if you have to go on vacation without me. If she had more room she would 100% keep me, but my foster sisters dont really want a little brother. If youd like to meet me, reach out to Northern Lakes Rescue and we can get together and see if this is a love match! Hudsons adoption fee is $350 which covers his neuter, vaccinations, microchip and any additional medical care he may have needed while in the rescues care. We are a foster based rescue, we do not house dogs at a facility. If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application on our website www.northernlakesrescue.org

animal.description:
***Please DO NOT send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available. If a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder- we are still accepting applications for them**

Meister is currently in Houston, TX and can transport to the PNW mid February.

Meister, 2 years old, male, pitbull, 43 lbs. This adorable dog was brought to our attention when he was placed on the euthanasia list in San Antonio, TX. We were able to spring him from the shelter life and are hoping to find his forever home in the PNW. 

Meister has been friendly with every dog he has met. He has been in a foster home with both male and female dogs. If the dog does not want to play with him, he leaves them alone. When Meister saw the dog in his foster home his face lit up and his body didn't stop wiggling. We think he would love a four legged friend to have as a companion. He does not seem overly playful and isn't needing an active playmate. 

He is friendly to both females and males and we've seen no aggression, fear or anxiety. We have no history with kids so we recommend a home with kids 10 years and older. 

Meister is housebroken, but has had some accidents when first in a home. He has done some marking as well, but we know he is a smart boy & will easily catch on once he's taught! He walks great on a leash. 

Meister loves to snuggle, give kisses and lounge around the house. He appears to have low/moderate energy and is not super active. 

Meister would make an amazing emotional support animal as he just loves being with his people! Meister does have separation anxiety and has managed to escape from several crates.  In doing so he has several cuts on his face as we believe we squeezed through  or pushed through the door. He has scratched up a door to get out of the room he was in to find his person. He will need someone who is home more than they are away. He will also need a secure crate/area where he can't get out or destroy anything in trying to get out. 
We would be willing to pay for one training session to help with this behavior with an agreed upon trainer in your area. 

We have no history with cats. 

Meister is an incredibly sweet dog who wants to be loved. We are hopeful someone will be willing to help ease his separation anxiety and will be able to see what an amazing dog he is.

***Listed BREED and AGE - We are taking our best guess on age, breed and size when fully grown. We rarely know a dog's exact age nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time.

The first step in our process is filling out an application. We will review your application as soon as we are able- there are two of us and we do the best that we can. We review applications on a first come first serve basis and look for the best fit/match for dog and applicant.

https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

animal.description: Hi! My name is Marley! I was rescued by the wonderful people at Big Dog Ranch from a hoarding house in Puerto Rico before arriving here at the ranch. I like to play with other dogs but can be very selective with who I choose to play with. I also tend to be very protective, particularly over my brothers and my space. I also am known to guard my resources (primarily food and water), usually due to a fear that they may be taken away from me. My protective behaviors are most likely due to living in an unstable environment for an extended period of time. I would really benefit from an experienced dog owner who is familiar with working with dogs who lived in difficult situations, thereby creating protective and fearful behaviors. The best fit for me would be an adult-only home without any other animals so that I can truly be the king of the castle. I would love to have a great big yard to run around and play in, but for the most part I think I would enjoy a quiet lifestyle in my new home. I would benefit from continued training to help me learn to be more confident in myself, which should translate to being more confident in my surroundings. I do appear to be potty trained but I have not thoroughly enjoyed learning how to walk on a leash yet, probably because I most likely have never seen a leash until I arrived here on the ranch, so I'm sure with further exposure I will get used to it.

animal.description:
Annie is a uniquely marked, brindle merle colored, 6 year old Great Dane girl coming into rescue due to some lifestyle changes within her family. Annie may be a little older but that means that this girl is already house trained, walks good on a leash and knows come, sit, stay, down and kennel up. She is good with other dogs, trustworthy with free roam, she doesn't bark, dig or chew on anything that she shouldn't and is good in the car. Annie doesn't like to be crated and she would do best in a home with dog door access and someone home more often than not. Due to the recent changes in her life she does get a little unsure and anxious in new situations but her foster family will be working with her to help her gain a little more confidence again. This sweet girl has some medical issues we will be getting her evaluated and helping her get the care she needs. Annie's favorite toys are a squeaky lion and stuffed animals and is happy as a clam to be play with them all day long.

animal.description:
Beautiful Chiba is a 7 year old Cane Corso Mastiff Mix that came to us from a shelter in Virginia, where she was surrendered by her owner that was moving. Chiba is a very large girl and came to us at least 50 pounds overweight. At one point, she was 80 pounds over! The vet thinks her goal weight is around 100 lbs. Due to the extra weight, Chiba is understandably less mobile and her foster family is working on helping her regain mobility and go on extra walks. Chiba is a friendly and sweet girl and likes to greet people with her little nubbin tail wagging! Her foster family is giving her some time to come out of her shell and she also needs entropion surgery and treatment for tick-borne illnesses, which will be done while she's in foster care. All this girl needs is a retirement home with a warm bed for her and good quality care for her remaining years. Can that be you?

Golden Rewards Program

All of our adoptable grey muzzled gentle giants who are at least 7 years young are available for adoption for a reduced $250 donation!

Already a Golden Rewards Club member? If you've adopted a senior gentle giant from Big Dogs Huge Paws in the past, we have great news for you! Adopt a second senior for a Golden Rewards Club adoption donation of $200, and if it's your third senior dog adoption we are offering a special Golden Rewards Club reduced donation of only $150! Why wait?

animal.description:
***Please DO NOT send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available. If a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder- we are still accepting applications for them**

Meister is currently in Houston, TX and can transport to the PNW mid February.

Meister, 2 years old, male, pitbull, 43 lbs. This adorable dog was brought to our attention when he was placed on the euthanasia list in San Antonio, TX. We were able to spring him from the shelter life and are hoping to find his forever home in the PNW. 

Meister has been friendly with every dog he has met. He has been in a foster home with both male and female dogs. If the dog does not want to play with him, he leaves them alone. When Meister saw the dog in his foster home his face lit up and his body didn't stop wiggling. We think he would love a four legged friend to have as a companion. He does not seem overly playful and isn't needing an active playmate. 

He is friendly to both females and males and we've seen no aggression, fear or anxiety. We have no history with kids so we recommend a home with kids 10 years and older. 

Meister is housebroken, but has had some accidents when first in a home. He has done some marking as well, but we know he is a smart boy & will easily catch on once he's taught! He walks great on a leash. 

Meister loves to snuggle, give kisses and lounge around the house. He appears to have low/moderate energy and is not super active. 

Meister would make an amazing emotional support animal as he just loves being with his people! Meister does have separation anxiety and has managed to escape from several crates.  In doing so he has several cuts on his face as we believe we squeezed through  or pushed through the door. He has scratched up a door to get out of the room he was in to find his person. He will need someone who is home more than they are away. He will also need a secure crate/area where he can't get out or destroy anything in trying to get out. 
We would be willing to pay for one training session to help with this behavior with an agreed upon trainer in your area. 

We have no history with cats. 

Meister is an incredibly sweet dog who wants to be loved. We are hopeful someone will be willing to help ease his separation anxiety and will be able to see what an amazing dog he is.

***Listed BREED and AGE - We are taking our best guess on age, breed and size when fully grown. We rarely know a dog's exact age nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time.

The first step in our process is filling out an application. We will review your application as soon as we are able- there are two of us and we do the best that we can. We review applications on a first come first serve basis and look for the best fit/match for dog and applicant.

https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
COURTESY POST 
16 year old Benjamin Franklin needs a new home.

I very recently rescued a 16 year old beagle from animal control with the intention of keeping him. 
He was in rough shape when I got him. He had been found hypothermic on the side of the road with a gaping hole in his side and a fair amount of hair loss. 

Since then  he has received his shots, heart worm check (-), and antibiotics for his side and ear Infections. He is healing up very nicely. He still has some dry skin but is getting better. He just needs 1 fish oil capsule in his food daily. 

Because it is very possible he has testicular cancer he will be neutered on feb 8th. I’m covering  all of the costs.

However what we have determined is that he needs to be in single dog household.  He doesn’t get along with other dogs. 

For interested adopters I will be asking for a veterinarian reference and will be doing a home visit at his potential adopters home.

His personality:  he is very loving, loves attention and to be petted. He loves walks but does pull some on the leash. He loves to sniff around outside.
He is a bit hard of hearing but can see just fine. Even though he isn’t currently neutered he never peed on anything in my home. He loves baths and treats. He even knows how to sit for treats. He loves to be next to his human on the couch or bed. He sleeps quite a bit. 

His name is currently Benjamin Franklin. 

Please contact me at (989) 450-7566 if you have questions or think they can provide him a loving home

**We are located in Tulsa, OK. We do not adopt puppies under 4 months out past 150 miles of Jenks, OK. Applications are found on our website at puppyhavenrescue.com**

Lola Bunny is a female heeler mix around 7 years old. She and her litter of pups were given up by their owner. Lola Bunny is just a super kind and loving little soul. She has learned so much in her short time with us. She absolutely loves the other dogs and the kids in her foster home. She will go lay down on her bed on command and sleeps through the night on her pet bed. It is believed she was a strictly outside dog before Puppy Haven, but despite that she has had zero accidents in the house.

She LOVES to chase after and catch tennis balls. She is extremely smart and eager to please. She has learned sit, shake and lay down since being with us. She has this cute quirky little “lean in” when she wants pet. She comes up to you, gives her paw and then just flops on you sideways. This girl loves to love!

She stays in her crate when her foster fam needs to go anywhere and has handled that fine as well. She is leash trained and does great on walks! She is going to make a family very happy. Although it might take her a moment to warm up to someone new since she is learning to trust humans, once she falls for you she is the most loving, sweet dog ever. She has not let her past affect her personality as she definitely has a ton of love she wants to give!

animal.description:
While my name may have a lot of the same letters, make no mistake, I am one of a kind! I am 1.5 year old, spayed Great Pyrenees Mix, who came into rescue with my sister, Biloxi. We were found abandoned behind a local store and were fortunate enough to have a nice lady rescue us and take us home. But now, that nice lady has to give us up because of some health issues...so here we are searching for our next forever home. I mainly have lived outside but am crate trained. I don't do so well with free-roam and do dig and chew when I am bored. I get along nicely with dogs and love children. I haven't lived with cats, so that is unknown. What is known however, is that I am super sweet! I also am very food motivated and will learn quickly with positive reinforcement. If you are ready for a one of a kind type of gal with double letters in her name, I am the one for you!

To see the most up to date adoption status of this dog, please visit www.bigdogshugepaws.com
This is just one of hundreds of gentle giants available for adoption at BDHPI! It is best not to get your heart set on any one particular dog upfront because there is no guarantee they will still be available once you are approved or that they are even the right match for your family. Purebred puppies are only eligible for adoption to giant breed experienced homes.

Duke is a very happy boy who absolutely adores other dogs and people. This stunning fellow was surrendered to one of the humane society's we work with due to his owner passing away.

Duke is energetic and enjoys activities where he can burn off some energy while still having your undivided attention. We believe he would do great with a family who has an active lifestyle and tons of love to give. He is a bit of a scaredy-cat when it comes to loud noises, so it doesn't take much to spook him. Duke loves to be included in whatever we do and really enjoys interacting with us. He may go explore the fields for a few minutes but then he comes back to check in with us and to say hi. He likes to make sure you're staying close by. 
This cutie pie gets cold easily during the colder months and loves to snuggle down in warm, fuzzy blankets before drifting off to sleep. 

Duke is so adorable and would be very happy in a home with a loving family and a fun doggie playmate.

Does handsome Duke sound like the guy for you?

animal.description:
Male American Staffordshire Terrier Mix

Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Approximate date of birth: 01/20/2015

Weight: 59.75 lbs

Children: Unknown 

Dogs: Yes

Cats: Unknown


Turin really enjoys being around other dogs and people but he also appreciates his alone time, which is usually spent wandering our fields. He is an independent fellow and everyone needs a little ''me'' time sometimes. He was found as a stray, was placed on a ''stray hold'' and when the microchip was scanned our partner shelter contacted the owner several times but never got a response. He's such a great dog and we are happy we could take him in.

Turin loves to explore our fields and soak up all the different scents and visuals surrounding us. He will come back to us for some pets and hugs but then he's off again to explore. He has a chill personality and he likes to relax and sunbathe in his outdoor kennel deck. Even though he is a low-key type of guy, he does have a good amount of energy and is athletic. If he was a person he would be in the NBA with his jumping skills. He for sure could slam dunk!

Does Turin sound like the companion you've been looking for?

animal.description:
Meet my handsome friend, Dogtown!

Dogtown is a 72lb boxer/pittie mix that is 2yo. He is the most submissive and empathetic boy. He is excellent with kiddos, tolerant of kitties, and also good with dog friends. Dogtown has some anxiety in new places; he showed it by some pacing and drooling. He is a velcro dog and loves to people please. Dogtown is housebroken and has been perfect in his crate; goes in on his own, no accidents, and silent. He does best in a plastic crate verses a wire crate as it makes him feel more secure and relaxed. Dogtown would be best suited in a home with a confident dog friend that will bring up his confidence and compliment his excessively submissive personality. A yin to his yang if you will ;) He is a loving boy and a joy to have as a guest in my home. Won't you choose him as your new best friend? To all potential Adopters, PLEASE read: These are difficult times for all Rescues. While we are healthy, our goal is to find EVERY husky their furever home. Due to the ONGOING INCREASE in COVID-19 cases in JAN 2021 we will be using a SAFE method for placing dogs in their new homes. As new Rescue Huskies are available the following will apply: Adoption Applications MUST be completed and reviewed before we schedule a 'Meet and Greet'. Applications are available by request. We require properly worn masks, gloves and any other PPE you would like to wear. Please do not be offended if we cannot place a husky with you at this point in time. It doesn't reflect on YOU as a pet owner...it's very difficult for us to provide the 'hands on', personal approach we're accustomed to. Have patience with us as we navigate these unusual times! Stay Safe! Thank You for understanding!

Interested in a Rescue dog? Please send an email and/or call 815-439-2313, press (star)* 2 and leave a message. (No calls after 8PM, please!)

Bluford is a male heeler. He was found as a stray and was surrendered to us. He’s full of energy and loves to play all the time. He does really well with the other dog in his foster home! He is very high energy and jumps when he gets really excited. His fosters are working on that but he’s not fully aware of how big he is. We advise against small children because of this. He doesn’t love getting into the crate and sometimes needs a little coaxing, but sleeps through the night just fine once he’s in there. When he’s not playing, he loves chewing on his Kong bones (and he is a heeler so having chew toys is a must!), or snuggling up on the couch. He gives lots of kisses and appreciates lots of pets.

He is working on leash training. He knows sit and is very treat motivated, so we are starting to work on other commands! He’s a gentle giant who would do really well in an active home or with another dog.

Colt came from a bad situation and is now doing well enough to go to his forever home. If that could be with you, please fill out an application today! 

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs are also microchipped.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

animal.description:
This handsome guy is going to make someone a wonderful new family member. Comet will win you over quickly when he bats his baby blues. We think he is a smooth collie mix. He is two years old and weighs in at 63 pounds but the vet tells us he could lose a few pounds. He is a very friendly boy. His former owners only had him for two weeks before they decided they didn't have enough time for him. They didn't even give him a chance!

Comet loves to run and play so a fully fenced yard is important. He will be a good walking or running partner for his new family as well.

He seems to be dog friendly so he would have fun with another canine family member. Of course, we will do meet and greets if an applicant has a dog to be sure they are a good fit. We have cat tested Comet and unfortunately he did not pass. So needs a home with no cats.

So, if you think Comet is the perfect new family member for you, come meet him on Saturdays from 10-2 at 809 Rockford Rd SW. He looks forward to visitors. If you are interested, we urge you to fill out an application prior to your visit.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi my name is Stella! I'm a very sweet and laid back, 2.5-year-old girl.
I was found as a stray so my background is unknown. I can be a bit shy at first meeting, but get over it fairly quickly. A few weeks after arriving at my foster home I had 4 seizures the day after I was spayed. We are not sure what triggered them but I am now on medication and have had no issues since. I actually look forward to taking my medication because my foster mom wraps it in cheese - and what dog doesn't LOVE cheese?!

I am still working on my manners. I did a little counter surfing and dumpster (trash can) diving for the first few days but I have been working on this and have only dove into the can once since then - it just all smells so good. I know some basic commands like sit and lay-down. I'm housebroken and mostly crate-trained. It takes me a few minutes to settle, but eventually I do. My foster family says I really no longer need the crate and that I am a really good girl when they are away. I just play with my fur sister and lay at the door until they get back. I play well with other dogs and my fur sister and I have lots of fun together. We do play little ruff at times, but love each other. My bark can be a little loud (high) when playing as I do get excited. I also love playing fetch but what German Shepherd doesn't?! I walk great on a leash and am very good in the car.

I do not get on the furniture and actually prefer to lay on the floor. Loud noises (beeping sounds, motorcycles, loud trucks and snoring) can make me pace if too loud - especially the loud snoring, which my foster mom says isn't too bad when she gets the room to herself with just the dogs haha. I like meeting new people and will bond quickly with my family! I have only been around one child and it wasn't for long but I seemed ok.

I have been around cats, but to me they are just indoor squirrels, so I try to chase them. Once I get used to a space and people, I am a great companion and will follow you anywhere!
Ideally, I want a backyard with a buddy to play with.

I am being fostered near Raleigh.
If you think you can offer me my furever home, please reach out to your adoption coordinator. If you do not have an adoption coordinator, please complete an adoption application at www.freedomgermanshepherdrescue.org

animal.description:
Duncan John, Duncan John, Duncan John...what a fine guy you are! 

Duncan John, although very loved by his young family in TN, they could no longer afford to keep him so he was surrendered to a shelter. According to shelter records he lived with children ages 6 and 8, but we haven't had him officially ""kid tested"" yet. He completely ignored the cats in their kennels during his cat test at the shelter, so he may get along with cats, but we cant be positive about that! With his intelligence, sweet demeanor, and good looks Duncan John quickly became a shelter favorite. 

Now he is ready to find his forever home! At 4 years old he is the perfect age- no longer a puppy but still his entire life left! He gets along well with other dogs, but does play a little rough sometimes so he needs a dog of equal energy level and understanding. He is crate trained and working hard on house training. He still pulls on a leash but with basic obedience training we expect him to do well. Duncan John loves to be loved on and gives the most gentle kisses. 

You know you need a Duncan John in your life so get your application in today!


Name: Duncan John
Breed: Pit Bull Terrier mix
Sex: Male
Age: 4 years old
Weight: 54 pounds
Spayed/Neutered: No
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Negative
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS: 
Good with Children: Has lived with children before but has not been around children in our care. 
Good with Dogs: Yes
Good with Cats: Unknown

Adoption Fee: $475.00


IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.


NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
**IF THE DOG IS POSTED, THEY ARE AVAILABLE! THE ADOPTION FEE IS LISTED ON THEIR PROFILE. PLEASE DO NOT EMAIL REGARDING FEE OR IF THE DOG IS STILL AVAILABLE**

**We are located in Tulsa, OK. We do not adopt puppies under 4 months out past 150 miles of Jenks, OK. Applications are found on our website at puppyhavenrescue.com**

Katie is a precious 11 month old lab. Katie was adopted out early in 2020 and returned a few months ago. We haven’t introduced her until now because Katie was returned due to a medical issue that we wanted to first understand.

Katie accidentally ingested raisins in her last home and was not seen by the vet in an urgent manner. This resulted in Katie going into renal failure as just a puppy.

While Katie does have special needs because of this, the vet has given her an 8-10 year life span and her condition is very manageable. She needs to be on a strict diet to help her kidneys for the rest of her life, but she isn’t on any medication at this time. Katie does drink an excessive amount of water due to the condition, so she needs to go out to potty multiple times throughout the day, more so than a regular dog would. Katie does not have any leaking and while she can hold her bladder throughout the night, her ideal home would have someone that is home most of the day to let her out when needed.

Katie may need to go back on meds in the future as she gets older, but we don’t know that for sure. Due to her young age, a lot of factors are unknown. What is known is that Katie is more than worth it for the right family.

Katie is very special. Her entire body wiggles with joy every time you come home, or when she’s getting extra loving. She loves to play with other dogs, both big and small, and know to be gentle around the smaller ones. Katie is smart, and wants to please. She loves working on commands and goes straight to her crate for dinner waiting patiently. She will sleep in her crate but prefers to be close to her humans.

This sweetheart just wants to be loved, and will stop everything for some belly rubs. She loves everyone she meets and is excellent with kids but will also alert you when strangers ring the door. If you are looking for a pet who will love you unconditionally, and show it every single day, Katie is your girl!

Unfortunately she and her little dog family had to be surrendered at the shelter in Riverton when her humans lost their housing and couldn't keep her. This girl has been very loved in the past and is just looking for a new start. She has lived with other dogs and cats and we are told that she has spent time around kids and done well. She is a gorgeous md/lg size and will make an excellent partner for all your outdoor adventures and indoor snuggle sessions. 

Please note, Animal Adoption Center cannot guarantee the breed, composition or ages of our dogs as we usually have no history prior to them entering the rescue. We make every effort to ensure the dogs are healthy.

Please know that our intention is to insure long lasting committed homes for the animals at the AAC. If we feel that an animal and a potential owner are not a good fit we reserve the right to refuse adoption.

-We require potential adopters to foster a dog for at least one night prior to adopting once they have an approved application submitted.
-We welcome out-of-area adopters, but please be aware we do require prospective adopters to come to our facility and meet the animal in person. You may either foster the dog locally in pet friendly lodging (preferably with any other dogs you own) or if you choose to drive the dog back home you agree to drive the dog back to Jackson if the dog isn't a good fit. Before you make the trip we encourage you to fill out an adoption application and submit it, to be sure you will qualify to adopt. Adoption applications can be filled out on our website. We cannot "hold" any animal. We have a "first qualified adopter can foster first" policy. 
-We will not ship animals. 
-Feel free to send over an inquiry or fill out an application for a dog you are interested in!

**IF THE DOG IS POSTED, THEY ARE AVAILABLE! THE ADOPTION FEE IS LISTED ON THEIR PROFILE. PLEASE DO NOT EMAIL REGARDING FEE, AGE, OR IF THE DOG IS STILL AVAILABLE**

**We are located in Tulsa, OK. We do not adopt puppies under 4 months out past 150 miles of Jenks, OK. Applications are found on our website at puppyhavenrescue.com**

Cherokee is a male Aussie mix around 10 months old. He was recently returned to us due to no fault of his own. Cherokee is the sweetest, loyal, lovable dog. He weighs about 70 pounds, and has the softest, prettiest brown fur that accompanies his beautiful green eyes. He is energetic and playful, but also can be chill and rest right by your side. He loves to go on walks, chase squirrels, and loves playing with other dogs. Playing fetch is one of his favorite things to do, and he also loves to chew on bones. He is a busy boy who loves to be your shadow and follow you everywhere you go. He loves car rides and playing at the dog park, but also loves cuddling in bed. He is very strong and is sure to beat you when playing tug of war!

Cherokee has had a few aggressive tendencies that are currently being worked through with a trainer. Because of this he would do best in a home with older children and experienced dog owners. He would do best with owners who are active, and would thrive in a home with other dogs who he can play with. He is crate trained, but prefers to be cozy on the couch and sleep on a dog bed. He has a lot of love to give, and is sure to bring joy to whoever adopts him!

Message us through the contact page or on Facebook to learn more about Cherokee!

animal.description:
In November Apple gave birth to 8 puppies in SC, and within days we got her to a safe foster home in NYC!

Now that Apples puppies have all been weened adopted, she gets to be her own dog in a very loving foster home. Apple herself is 2 years old and about 48 pounds full grown. Apples foster family has nothing but wonderful things to share about this gorgeous Hound Mix. She can be timid around new people, but when she gets to know you she is incredibly sweet. She is smart, and picks up new tricks in just a couple of days (as long as you have a treat handy ). While being an excellent mom to her puppies shes worked on her housebreaking, learned sit, and has improved on her recall skills. She is still a bit skittish with sudden noises or movements but is comforted by affection from humans. Apple was very skinny when we pulled her from the shelter so shes still working on filling in her frame! She is extremely athletic and would make a great jogging buddy. She can climb and jump very high with those long legs of her. Apple prefers to be around her humans and does howl and cry when left. She is working on her crate training and separation anxiety, and would prefer a home where people are more around to love on her! Apple is wonderful with other playful dogs and always loves to hang out to play with them. We are currently looking for an adopter or foster to adopt home for Apple with another dog to play with! She is so snuggly and loving and can’t wait to share all her love in a forever home!

We are currently facilitating safe adoptions with COVID-19 protocols and adopt out to NYC and surrounding states only - NY CT PA & NJ. 

**If a dog is listed on petfinder as available then we are still accepting applications for that dog. We urge you to apply as soon as possible to be considered to adopt the dog you’re interested **

Thank you for wanting to give one of our adoptables a loving home! Please follow us on Instagram at @rescuecity for more adoptable updates!

animal.description:
Latte is a very sweet girl, looking for an extra special forever home. She
is a 1.5 year old Chihuahua mix who weighs 13.9 pounds and is full grown.
Because she was trapped as a stray, Latte will be slow to warm up. She is okay with kids, although she would prefer older, dog savvy children. Once she comes out of her shell, Latte is an incredibly loving and energetic dog! She will need to be in a patient home with a family willing to work with her in several areas. Latte will need help in breaking a bad chewing habit. She loves to play with toys, and would do best in a home with a family who can spend lots of time playing with her. Latte is good with other dogs and would like to be in a home with at least one other energetic canine companion to help keep her occupied. Other than playing with toys and other dogs, Latte likes to nap, and she is more than happy to hang out close to her humans while they're working. Unfortunately, Latte doesn't walk well on a leash, so she will need leash training and a securely fenced in backyard in her forever home.
She is spayed, up to date on vaccines, microchipped and vet checked. Her adoption fee of $200 includes a complimentary vet visit. To potentially adopt, please contact her foster mom at
pennig@cox.net

animal.description:
Yes, yes, stop staring. My head is as big as it looks or bigger and my jowls are part of my charm. When I say charm, I mean the trail of water that is behind me when I drink and the food crumbs that lead you to me. But, you know, that is what makes me me-Perkunas-the Baltic God of thunder. When I bay when I'm excited, it does sound deep, but I wouldn't quite say thunder. And, believe me, when you come home, I am soooooooooooooooo excited to see you. One of the few times I get super excited is when you let me out of my crate. Other than that, I'm pretty mellow. Though, I want to be your shadow- an 80 plus pound shadow, so I'm a wee bit noticeable. Barely, noticeable - especially when I'm in bed cuddling with you. And boy do I like to cuddle and be loved on. Currently, I live in a home with dogs 13 pounds up to my size. Haven't quite learned how to play with my buddies, even though I'm only about a year and a half. In general, I'm pretty low key and only moderate energy. I do need a bit of training, but nothing too shabby and I'm still learning my toilet manners, but that won't take long. Mostly just love on me, let me chew on my toys, and let me be your very best friend in the whole world! Oh, lastly, I do have those pesky heart,worms, but that is being treated and won't take me long to be back at full health!

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online. http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Bella! Are you my new forever home? I sure hope so!
My  foster says I am a young 9-year old with plenty of spunk and love to share. I recently relocated to the Pacific  NW after I got separated from my owners during the California wildfires. I am  very calm and quiet. I don’t have much to say so I hardly bark, although I have  been known to snore. I am fully house trained and have been working on my  crate training, occasionally am even spotted hanging out in there for a quick  snooze. My foster family tells me how polite and smart I am, I always sit when  they ask and we have been learning some cool new tricks during our free time. I  am extremely affectionate and love to sit right at your feet, whether you  are working or watching TV. But I also understand that I can’t always be  near you and will quietly hang out in my own space while you are  tending to other responsibilities. I’ll admit, I do get anxious around other dogs  and cats are much too fun to chase, so I need a home where I’m the only  four-legged pet. My foster home has been working with a trainer to help understand my  discomfort around other dogs, so we are focusing our training within the boundaries of our own backyard so I can give them my full attention. Walks outside of our yard tend to be overwhelming, so I will need an adopter that has a securely fenced yard, preferably not see through, so I can  continue my training and work towards building up my comfort level so that we can  have enjoyable walks through our neighborhood in the future. I am a sensitive gal and  need an understanding adopter who will enjoy our life together at home, as I may  never be an outdoorsy kind of gal. I believe in being kind, polite, and  respectful, and I promise I will stay that way with you! I would be content to just  quietly sit in the same room with you and bonus if there is a comfy place to  sleep. Of course, a good neck scratch or some peanut butter is always welcome too.  And if you’re really feeling generous, I like to stay warm and toasty, so I’d happily strut my stuff in a cozy sweater. I know with patience I’ll find  my perfect home, and my people describe me as very deserving of that. If  you want to see more pictures and videos of me, check out my Instagram  page, @bella_the_lil_piggy 
 
Your future best friend,
Bella

If you are interested in meeting or learning more about BELLA please email OUR FOSTER TEAM

animal.description:
Looking for a handsome man to make your life complete? Meet our boy Dusty. He is a 5 year old, 18 pound, tan and white, Chihuahua/JRT mix. He is a happy boy and a true LAP DOG! He is happy to be your one and only love but if you have another dog, he prefers calm female companions. He enjoys walking on a leash and riding in the car. He does not like to be left alone! His previous owner adopted him from the shelter but brought him to us because his large dog did not take to Dusty and was afraid he would harm him. We adopted him out but he was returned after 10 months when his owner lost her house. He unfortunately had spent his days outdoors and was only allowed to sleep inside at night. This is a NO NO! He is an INDOOR ONLY dog! He does enjoy playing ball! He definitely likes to cuddle with his person. Perfect for a family and especially retired folks, someone that can commit to him FOREVER! He puts up with cats but doesn't really like them. He is housetrained and will let you know he needs to go potty. He is neutered, microchipped and up to date on vaccinations. Dusty will be a wonderful companion for an active individual or a family, children over 10 years of age. Photography by Camryns Captures OFFICE

animal.description:
Meet Smeagle!

This boy just arrived to us from our shelter partner in Arkansas.   
He is a friendly social boy that does well with other dogs.   He is a typical low energy easy senior dog.   So if you are looking for calm companionship consider Smeagle

Our vet looked at him and is guess he is between 10 and 13yrs old.
He has an old ear hematoma that healed on it's own which is why he has one shriveled ear.  He has some hair loss on his back end that they think is from flea dermatitis from awhile ago.  He is flea free now so she thinks his hair will grow back with good nutrition and consistent flea prevention.  
His teeth are pretty worn down and may be causing him some pain.   We have been giving him softened kibble and wet food. 
She noticed he has some sensitivity in his hips.  

You can see from this video he likes his ear scratched: https://youtu.be/Va8Fa1J3V1A

He is up to date on vaccines and rabies.  His neuter is scheduled for next week.

He is at a foster home in Griffith, IN if you would like to meet him fill out the application below

**We do offer a Senior for Senior program.  If you are 65 and older and adopt a pet 7 years and older the adoption fee is 1/2 price.  $75 for Smeagle


Adoption Process:

- please fill out our adoption application: https://www.dayofthedogs.org/adoption-application

- one of our team members will get back to you. 

- our dogs can be seen by appointment only after an approved application has been received.

- Adoption fee helps to cover spay/neuter, initial vaccines, rabies, initial worming, and microchip.

-We cannot place holds on our dogs. Please do not contact us until you are prepared to adopt.

NOTE:  We are very good about updating the pet's profiles once adopted.  So no need to write us to ask "Is he/she still available?"  If the post is up, the dog is still available. 

About Us:
Day of the Dogs is a 501c3 nonprofit that is dedicated to helping shelters increase live release.  We coordinate 2 - 4 transports per month from TX, OK and AR to NW Indiana/Chicagoland area.  We do direct adoptions ourselves out of Dyer, IN area and partner with 12 other rescues and shelters in both IL and IN that are willing to help southern pets in need.   
We rely on donations to help fund our ongoing transports.  Please donate if you can.  Every dollar adds up and we are grateful for any help we can get: https://www.paypal.com/paypalme/DayoftheDogs

Roxy was surrendered to the Mesquite Shelter along with her sister Harleigh by their owner as they were deemed "too much responsibility". These girls came to us in the worst condition, severe mange and skin infection from fleas and overall lack of care. 

Roxy's condition had zero affect on her energy level however, as she loves to play and run as long as you let her. You wouldn't know it from her skeptical, side-eye glances at the camera, but you can't keep her from smiling when shes playing or cuddling up to you. As long as you have a Milkbone in your pocket you're her BFF no matter who you are. Roxy's new home will need a nice fenced back yard where she can run and explore. Roxy is crate trained and graduated from basic obedience class where she was a class favorite.

animal.description:
*****************************************************************
PLEASE READ THOROUGHLY BEFORE INQUIRING
*****************************************************************

--ABOUT SCOOBY--
Scooby is a handsome young goofball from South Carolina! He loves everyone he meets; humans and pups! He does like to play hard so roommates of any species will need to be sturdy and confident enough to handle him. He loves to wrestle and do zoomies with his dog pals, and would love a large fenced in yard to run in! He would not do well in small homes or apartments; this big boy needs plenty of room to romp around! He still needs some help with basic training, like not jumping to say hello, proper leash walking, and is mastering potty training. Luckily he is food motivated and eager to learn!

Key Notes:
-2-year old neutered male.
-Unknown breed mix.
-70 pounds and a healthy weight.
-Found as a stray in South Carolina.
-No apartment style or small homes. A large fenced-in yard is ideal.
-Has not been around kids yet, but should not live with any younger than 12.
-Good with sturdy and playful dogs; very playful and a little pushy.
-No more than 6 hours alone a day; will need a potty and play break.
-Experience with dogs recommended.
-Medium-high energy; loves lots of playtime but will snuggle when his energy is burnt.
-Almost housebroken.
-Very strong on leash; better with a no-pull harness.
-Food motivated; knows "sit".
-Jumps on people to greet and playfully.
-Basic obedience training recommended.

--THE ADOPTION PROCESS--
If you are interested in adopting this animal, please submit an online application. Applications will be reviewed as received. If in our opinion a pet is a good candidate for you, an adoption counselor will contact you to schedule a zoom chat. If you do not hear from us it simply means either the animal has been adopted or we have not received the right pet for you. The application process is at no charge to you and only needs to be completed once as all applications will be kept on file.

Online applications can be found here: www.buddydoghs.com/forms

Check out our FAQ for answers to most questions here: www.buddydoghs.com/faq

Adopters must be at least 21 years of age and a Massachusetts resident.

animal.description:
Meet Sage! 

Interested in meeting Sage? 

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Age appropriate vaccinations
- Heartworm test (for dogs over 6mo) and treatment if positive
- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

*Please note that the identified breed(s) are best guesses. We very rarely have information on our dogs' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays.*

animal.description: Meet Jakova! She is around 1 year old and is a pretty Shepherd mix. While it takes her a moment to warm up in new situations, once she's settled in, she's as sweet as can be. She is easy to handle on leash and rides well in the car. Jakova is house trained and crated trained in her current foster home. She is kid friendly and, while she isn't a super snuggly dog, she does like attention. She has medium energy and the stamina to go for 3 mile jogs with her foster dad in her foster home. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Jakova, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
Meet Bailey the sweetest 5 year old doxie mix!
Bailey hasn't had the best life so far. She has been neglected much of her life. She came to us with nails so long they curled over, covered in fleas. She has been kept in a cage most of her life and if not in a cage, roaming the neighborhood streets or locked in a garage. She would get reprimanded and hit for peeing and pooping in her cage, yet was never let out to go potty. According to her foster mom, she is fully potty trained and even goes to the door to tell you she needs to go. She has not had one mistake yet! She has some healed wounds on her face, chest and forehead, of unknown origin, but we can only imagine how she got them.

Bailey has gotten a taste of the good life, and she loves it! Bailey would love to go to a home with children and another dog(s) - she's even great with cats. She loves family life and free life outside of her cage. Her foster family has chickens and farm animals and she does not chase or go after them at all. Bailey loves car rides and the moment you open your door, she'll hop right in! Her front paws turn out and the vet says that is a common birth defect but that doesn't stop her! We would like Bailey to go to a calm home where there is no yelling and tension, as that makes her very nervous, given her upbringing. She was left alone most of her life and we never want that again for this sweet girl.

If you are ready to open up your heart to 25lbs of pure love please visit www.MaxxandMe.org to complete an adoption application.

Bailey is spayed, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped. Her adoption donation is only $250! As with all puppies adopted through Maxx & Me, her adopter will need to commit to continue working with a positive reinforcement trainer of their choice to help her continue to become a well mannered and confident girl.

Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

Meet Jordy! 

Jordy is a 5 year-old Bulldog mix. He’s doing well learning commands of “sit” and “here” and easily goes into his crate when directed. He’s learning to play well with other dogs. Loves to sit close to his people. He’s a sweetheart!

Interested in meeting Jordy? 

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Age appropriate vaccinations
- Heartworm test (for dogs over 6mo) and treatment if positive
- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

*Please note that the identified breed(s) are best guesses. We very rarely have information on our dogs' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays.*

animal.description: Romy is a one year old white shepherd husky mix.  He loves to be busy and would run for hours with you if you wanted him to. He can be entertained while playing with his Kong or a bone and won’t chew inappropriate things if you give him an ample supply of things he can chew on. He loves a plastic bottle with frozen treats in it that he can open and destroy while he’s outside! He’s still earning his space in the house and isn’t left unattended in a room where there are things he’ll be tempted to chew.  He is not aggressive and is crate trained and house trained. Amazingly loud noises like thunder and fireworks barely take his notice. He does ok with other dogs, but is persistent and needs help learning when to take a play break. Does fairly well on a leash. Cats are a mystery and I wouldn't recommend for families with real little kids as he has no boundaries, but again he's not aggressive. He requires a fully fenced yard and a family with lots of love to offer.  He needs someone to help him learn to be calm and greet people without jumping or mouthing people’s hands. He's up to date on all his shots, heartworm and flea meds, he's neutered.  If you are seriously interested in Romy, please go to www.pawswithpride.org and complete our online application. His adoption fee is $150.00  We will get back to you asap. We DO NOT adopt out of the State of Ohio!
